"Bataille","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Brunel, Celine, Jacques.","French: nickname for a bellicose man, from <i>bataille</i> ‘battle’ (from Latin <i>battualia</i>), or a habitational name from (La) Bataille, the name of several places in France, all named as the site of a battle in former times.","West Indian (mainly Haiti): nickname from French <i>bataille</i> ‘battle’ (compare 1 above)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Henry de Bataille was born in 1158, in Fawdon, Northumberland, England. He married Lady. Henry de Bataille about 1178, in Northumberland, England, United Kingdom. He died in 1207, in Fawdon, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 49."},"et":{"1158–1207":"1158–1207","1160–1207":"1160–1207","1158–Female":"1158–Surnud","1188–1250":"1188–1250","1158":"1158","Abt 1178":"umbes 1178","1188":"1188","1250":"1250","1160":"1160","1207":"1207","Fawdon, Northumberland, England, United Kingdom":"Fawdon, Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Fawdon, Northumberland, England":"Fawdon, Northumberland, England",", Northumberland, England, British Isles":"Northumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1158–1207":"1158–1207","1160–1207":"1160–1207","1158–Female":"1158–Kuollut","1188–1250":"1188–1250","1158":"1158","Abt 1178":"